<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Docker Terms</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="../style.css"> <!-- Linking external CSS -->
</head>
<body>

  <h1>Ansible Inventory</h1>
  <p>Inventory is a file that contains the list of servers (hosts) Ansible manages.</p>

  <h2>Types of Inventory in Ansible</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Static Inventory</li>
    <li>Dynamic Inventory</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Static Inventory</h2>
  <p><strong>Simple Meaning:</strong> A static inventory is a manually created file where you define servers.</p>
  <p><strong>Default Location:</strong> <code>/etc/ansible/hosts</code></p>

  <h3>Example 1: Simple Static Inventory</h3>
  <pre>
web1
web2
db1
  </pre>
  <p>Run command:</p>
  <pre>ansible all -m ping</pre>

  <h3>Example 2: Grouped Inventory</h3>
  <pre>
[webservers]
web1
web2

[dbservers]
db1
db2
  </pre>
  <p>Run command:</p>
  <pre>ansible all -m ping</pre>

  <h3>Example 3: Inventory with Variables</h3>
  <pre>
[webservers]
web1 ansible_user=ec2-user ansible_port=22
web2 ansible_user=ec2-user ansible_port=22
  </pre>

  <h3>Example 4: Production Style Inventory</h3>
  <pre>
[sap_app]
app01
app02

[sap_db]
db01

[sap_cluster]
node01
node02
  </pre>

  <div class="note">
    ✅ <strong>When to Use Static Inventory:</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Small environments</li>
      <li>Fixed servers</li>
      <li>On-prem setups</li>
    </ul>
  </div>


###############################


  <h1>Dynamic Inventory</h1>
  <p><strong>Simple Meaning:</strong> Dynamic inventory automatically fetches server details from cloud or external sources. You don’t manually write servers.</p>

  <h2>Why Needed?</h2>
  <p>In cloud environments (AWS/Azure):</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Servers are created/deleted frequently</li>
    <li>IPs change</li>
    <li>Manual inventory is not practical</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Example: AWS Dynamic Inventory</h3>
  <pre>
plugin: aws_ec2
regions:
  - ap-south-1
  </pre>

  <p>Run command:</p>
  <pre>ansible-inventory -i aws_ec2.yml --graph</pre>

  <h3>Example Output</h3>
  <pre>
@all:
  |--@aws_ec2:
  |  |--ec2-13-45-67-89.compute.amazonaws.com
  |  |--ec2-98-76-54-32.compute.amazonaws.com
  </pre>

  <h3>Example: Azure Dynamic Inventory</h3>
  <pre>
plugin: azure_rm
include_vm_resource_groups:
  - myResourceGroup
  </pre>

  <h3>Real Production Example</h3>
  <p>In AWS:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>New EC2 instances spin up automatically</li>
    <li>Ansible fetches them dynamically</li>
    <li>Runs patching or configuration</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="note">
    ✅ <strong>When to Use Dynamic Inventory:</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Cloud environments (AWS, Azure, GCP)</li>
      <li>Auto-scaling systems</li>
      <li>Large infrastructure</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Additional Types (Important for Interview)</h2>

  <h3>INI Format Inventory</h3>
  <pre>
[web]
web1
web2
  </pre>

  <h3>YAML Inventory</h3>
  <pre>
all:
  children:
    webservers:
      hosts:
        web1:
        web2:
  </pre>

  <h3>Host Variables & Group Variables</h3>
  <p><strong>Host Variables</strong></p>
  <pre>web1 ansible_user=ubuntu</pre>

  <p><strong>Group Variables</strong></p>
  <pre>
[webservers]
web1
web2

[webservers:vars]
ansible_user=ubuntu
  </pre>

  <h3>Real Production Example (Complete)</h3>
  <pre>
[webservers]
web1 ansible_host=10.0.0.1
web2 ansible_host=10.0.0.2

[dbservers]
db1 ansible_host=10.0.1.1

[all:vars]
ansible_user=ec2-user
ansible_ssh_private_key_file=/home/user/key.pem
  </pre>

  <h2>⭐ Static vs Dynamic Inventory</h2>
  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Feature</th>
      <th>Static</th>
      <th>Dynamic</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Server list</td>
      <td>Manual</td>
      <td>Automatic</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Best for</td>
      <td>Small environments</td>
      <td>Cloud / large environments</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Maintenance</td>
      <td>Manual</td>
      <td>Auto</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Example</td>
      <td>hosts file</td>
      <td>AWS plugin</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

</body>
</html>

